  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>What salary should you pay yourself?</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The arithmetic always points at the lowest number. That is exactly why it is not the answer.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    An S corporation owner takes some profit as salary, which carries payroll tax, and the rest as a
    distribution, which does not. Lower the salary and the tax falls. There is no point on the curve where
    that stops being true, so any calculator promising an optimal salary is telling you to go as low as
    you dare.
  </p>
  <p>
    The constraint is not arithmetic, it is the reasonable compensation rule: your salary has to be
    defensible for the work you actually do. Set it too low and the tax authority can reclassify the
    difference and charge back payroll tax with interest and penalties. So this shows the whole range and
    what each choice is worth, and leaves the judgement where it belongs.
  </p>

  <p class="section-label">Calculator</p>
  <ScorpSalaryCalculator client:load />

  <h2>What makes a salary defensible</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>What you would have to pay someone else to do your job.</li>
    <li>The hours you actually work in the business, and what share of the profit your own labour generates rather than capital or staff.</li>
    <li>Comparable pay in your industry and region — this is the evidence that matters if the figure is ever questioned.</li>
    <li>Consistency. A salary that moves inversely to profit every year describes the strategy rather than the work.</li>
  </ul>

